alwaysApply: true
---

Project: Airbnkey

Description:
Airbnkey is a modern showcase website for a short-term rental management company in Cannes.
The website displays apartments with photos, structured details, and an interactive map.
This project must stay simple, elegant, maintainable, and ready to evolve into a more professional product later.

Tech stack:
- Next.js 16 App Router
- React 19
- TypeScript
- pnpm
- Tailwind CSS
- shadcn/ui
- next/image

General philosophy:
- Prefer simple, robust, and maintainable code
- Prefer boring, proven solutions over clever or exotic ones
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions
- Avoid over-engineering
- Avoid premature optimization
- Keep the architecture clean and easy to evolve
- Prioritize readability and maintainability over cleverness

Architecture rules:
- Use Next.js App Router correctly
- Prefer Server Components by default
- Use Client Components only when interactivity requires them
- Keep client boundaries small and explicit
- Keep logic close to where it is used
- Avoid global state unless there is a clear need
- Prefer local state with React hooks
- Reuse existing components before creating new ones
- Keep components focused on a single responsibility
- Favor composition over deeply nested abstractions

Project structure:
- app/: routes, layouts, page-level composition
- app/components/: UI components specific to the app
- data/: static or local data sources
- types/: shared TypeScript types
- public/apartments/: apartment images
- lib/: only for reusable helpers or pure utility functions if needed

Structure rules:
- Do not invent new folders unless they are clearly justified
- Do not move files unnecessarily
- Do not create complex architectural layers for a simple feature
- Keep the current project organization stable and predictable

Component design rules:
- Components must be small, reusable, and easy to read
- Separate presentational concerns from stateful logic when useful
- Do not create components that are too generic too early
- Do not create "manager", "controller", or "provider" components unless truly necessary
- Avoid prop drilling only when it becomes a real problem, not preemptively
- Prefer explicit props over hidden magic

React rules:
- Use idiomatic React patterns
- Use useState for local interactive state
- Use useMemo or useCallback only when there is a real performance reason
- Do not add hooks just for style
- Avoid unnecessary effects
- Do not use useEffect when plain render logic is sufficient
- Avoid derived state when it can be computed directly
- Do not duplicate source of truth

TypeScript rules:
- Use clear and strict TypeScript types
- Prefer explicit domain types
- Avoid any
- Avoid overly complex generic types
- Keep types readable and practical
- Reuse existing domain types instead of redefining similar shapes
- Model the domain simply and clearly

Next.js rules:
- Follow App Router best practices
- Keep page files focused on composition
- Keep routing simple
- Use next/image for images unless there is a strong reason not to
- Use next/link for navigation
- Prefer built-in Next.js capabilities before adding third-party solutions
- Be careful with server/client boundaries
- For browser-only libraries, isolate them inside client components
- When integrating browser-only tools like maps, use dynamic import if necessary to avoid SSR issues

Styling rules:
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling
- Use shadcn/ui components when they fit the use case
- Keep styling consistent, minimal, and elegant
- Prefer utility classes over custom CSS unless truly needed
- Avoid excessive visual complexity
- Keep spacing, typography, radius, and shadows consistent
- UI should feel modern, clean, and close to Airbnb-style simplicity

Design principles:
- Mobile-first responsive design
- Clear visual hierarchy
- Good spacing and alignment
- Accessible interactions
- Simple, polished UI over flashy UI
- Prefer a professional product feel over a demo feel

Accessibility rules:
- Use semantic HTML
- Ensure dialogs, buttons, and interactive elements are accessible
- Always include required accessibility elements for shadcn/ui components
- Respect keyboard interactions when relevant
- Do not break focus behavior
- Use meaningful alt text for images

Image rules:
- Always use next/image for apartment images
- Images live in /public/apartments
- Do not use raw img tags unless absolutely necessary
- Keep image usage simple and predictable
- Avoid unnecessary image wrappers
- Use responsive image sizing when appropriate
- Be mindful of LCP for above-the-fold images

Data rules:
- Apartment data currently comes from local files in data/
- Keep the data model simple and structured
- Do not introduce a database, CMS, or API layer unless explicitly requested
- Reuse the existing apartment domain model
- Do not scatter business data across many files without need

Map rules:
- Use MapLibre GL JS for maps
- Do not introduce heavy or unnecessary map abstractions
- Reuse the existing apartment data for markers
- Keep map integration simple and isolated
- Reuse the existing apartment dialog/modal when opening apartment details from the map

Performance rules:
- Avoid unnecessary client-side JavaScript
- Keep dependencies minimal
- Avoid heavy third-party libraries unless clearly justified
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Prefer simple solutions that perform well by default
- Be careful with image loading, hydration, and browser-only code

Dependency rules:
- Do not install a new library unless it is clearly necessary
- Before suggesting a dependency, prefer native Next.js, React, Tailwind, or shadcn/ui solutions
- Avoid trendy libraries when a simple local implementation is enough
- If a library is truly needed, choose a well-known and lightweight one

Code quality rules:
- Write clean, explicit, production-minded code
- Keep functions short and focused
- Use clear naming
- Avoid dead code
- Avoid duplicated logic
- Avoid magic values when a named constant improves clarity
- Prefer straightforward control flow
- Leave the codebase simpler than before
- When modifying code, preserve consistency with the existing style

Decision-making rules:
- When proposing or implementing a solution, choose the simplest robust approach
- Do not introduce architecture for hypothetical future needs
- Do not optimize for scale that does not yet exist
- Prefer incremental improvements
- Respect the current scope of the project

For any implementation:
- First think about the simplest maintainable solution
- Prefer clarity over novelty
- Respect the existing architecture
- Do not surprise the developer with unnecessary changes